Use a real in-memory local server and two memory-backed clients. Write several rows through Alice, await each write at `tier: "edge"`, then use `vi.waitFor` to query Bob at the edge tier. Normalize the received rows by a stable key before asserting, since result order is not behavior under test.

```ts
const expected = ["a", "b", "c"];
await Promise.all(
  expected.map((title) => alice.insert(app.todos, { title }).wait({ tier: "edge" })),
);

await vi.waitFor(async () => {
  const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
  expect(rows.map((row) => row.title).sort()).toEqual(expected);
});
```

Shut down both clients and stop the server in teardown; do not use sleeps or assert query order.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` with two local-first sessions. Create Alice’s row through Alice so ownership metadata is established; assert Bob’s read is filtered out and Bob’s mutations reject.

```ts
const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
const row = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice only" }).value;

await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);
bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Bob edit" }));
bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.todos, row.id));
```

Also retain an Alice allowed-write assertion to prove the test row and policy path are valid. Clean up with `testApp.shutdown()`.
